  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions evolved gradually over several decades:\n\n1. Early Foundations:\n- Initially emerged from efforts to combat organized crime in the 1930s\n- Focused on tracking financial transactions related to illegal activities\n- United States passed initial regulatory frameworks during Prohibition era\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Created framework for tracking suspicious financial activities\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as global problem\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Major Turning Point - Anti-Money Laundering Act (1986):\n- Criminalized money laundering as specific federal offense\n- Expanded governmental investigative powers\n- Increased penalties for financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced surveillance and reporting requirements\n- Increased international cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n6. Ongoing Global Efforts:\n- Continuous refinement of international regulatory frameworks\n- Increased technological sophistication in tracking financial transactions\n- Growing emphasis on cryptocurrency and digital financial crime prevention",
